Statistical Significance for Source Detection
----------------------------------------------
How many standard deviations away from the mean background value must a pixel be to confidently identify it as a real astronomical source rather than noise?

Background Statistics:
- Image size: 4611 × 2570 pixels = 11,850,270 total pixels
- Background mean: μ = 3421.3 counts
- Background standard deviation: σ = 20.1 counts
- Distribution: Approximately Gaussian

Analysis:
For a Gaussian distribution, the probability of exceeding a threshold by chance:
- 1σ: 16% of pixels (too many false detections)
- 2σ: 2.5% of pixels → ~296,000 false detections in this image
- 3σ: 0.15% of pixels → ~17,775 false detections
- 5σ: 0.00006% of pixels → ~7 false detections

Detection Thresholds for this image:
- 2σ threshold: 3421.3 + 2(20.1) = 3461.5 counts
- 3σ threshold: 3421.3 + 3(20.1) = 3481.6 counts
- 5σ threshold: 3421.3 + 5(20.1) = 3521.8 counts

Conclusion:
A minimum of 2σ is required to distinguish sources from noise, as lower thresholds produce too many false positives. In practice, 3-5σ is standard in astronomy:
- 3σ: Good balance between detecting faint sources and limiting false detections
- 5σ: Very reliable detections, but may miss fainter sources

The large number of pixels (12 million) means even statistically rare events occur frequently, necessitating higher thresholds. Real sources are further distinguished by having multiple adjacent pixels above threshold, not just isolated high-value pixels. The number of standard deviations does not have to be integer.

